FG-91 — Read the Panel’s Signals (Questions • Time • Who)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: What the panel asks—and how long—predicts the order you can win.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Track who asks (proceduralist vs. pragmatist), how long on each issue, and what they repeat (standard vs. remedy). Pivot your close to the dominant signal.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 3-row “signal log” from your last OA video/audio: Judge • Topic • Time • Quote/pin.
	•	✅ Model Response: “J2: 6 min on ‘not reached’ harm → close with limited-remand block.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Questions forecast relief—aim your order there.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A heat map bar with one issue glowing.

⸻

FG-92 — The First 60 Seconds (Ask • Standard • Pins • Relief)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Open with your entire case in four beats.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Ask (one line) → Standard (one cite) → Two pins (Dkt/Tab) → Relief (two lines). Stop; let questions land.
	•	📝 Assignment: Script your 60-second open; keep to ≤75 words.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Abuse (wrong test). Pins: Dkt 18:2; Tab 3 p.2. Relief: vacate & remand 21 days for harm findings.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: A clean minute anchors a messy hour.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A stopwatch with four labeled ticks.

⸻

FG-93 — Draft Long, Cut to One Screen
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Write the full thought, then cut to what signs.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Draft a long paragraph; highlight pins; delete adjectives; keep only SoR + 2 pins + remedy. Put the long version in notes, not the filing.
	•	📝 Assignment: Reduce a 180-word section to ≤70 words with one pin per sentence.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Wrong test (cite). Harm not reached (Dkt 18:2). Remand 21d for findings.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Cutting is advocacy.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Scissors trimming a page to a tight card.

⸻

FG-94 — Timeline Addendum (With Capture & Hash)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A hashed timeline turns dates into proof.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Table: Date • Event • Pin • Effect; footer: captured [date] + SHA-256; place as Add. Tab A and cite it.
	•	📝 Assignment: Produce a 10-row timeline addendum; add hash at the bottom.
	•	✅ Model Response: “08/15 Rule 58 (Dkt 95:1) → 30-day clock; SHA-256 41be22… (captured 08/19).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Dates + hash = fewer fights.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A simple table with a fingerprint footer.

⸻

FG-95 — Public Note After OA (Documents, Not Drama)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Tell the public what happened, where to verify, what’s next—no spin.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: 120 words: date, issues discussed, two hashed links (brief/appendix page or OA packet), next step window.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft your OA note with two document pins.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Panel focused on harm not reached (Dkt 18:2). OA packet hash … Next: limited-remand request if needed.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Calm documents build trust.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two document tiles with tiny fingerprint icons.

⸻

FG-96 — Misquote Fix (Transcript • Pin • One-Line Correction)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Correct the line, not the case.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Identify page:line, quote “as transcribed” vs. “should read,” pin the record page; no merits expansion; request corrected transcript/page.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 6-line correction for one misquote.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Tr. 12:14–18 ‘reached harm’ → ‘did not reach harm’; record Dkt 18:2; corrected page requested.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Precision preserves credibility.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A redline bubble on a single transcript line.

⸻

FG-97 — Split Map (Two Columns • One Line per Court)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Show the conflict on a one-page table, not in prose.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Columns: Side A / Side B; each row: court • ≤10-word holding • cite; put your holding line above.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 6-row split map for your issue.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Holding: factor-tied findings required. 9th—required (cite); 5th—omission allowed (cite).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Editors love maps.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A two-column chart with short pin tags.

⸻

FG-98 — Relief Text Bank (Versioned & Forum-Specific)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Maintain signable snippets for each forum & posture.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Keep bank entries tagged by forum (state/fed/agency) and posture (stay, remand, clarify); version and date; paste, don’t compose live.
	•	📝 Assignment: Create 5 snippets (vacate/remand; clarify; admin stay; costs; mandate note).
	•	✅ Model Response: “Vacate & remand for findings on (a)–(d) within 21 days; status ≤3 pp.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Prepared language wins minutes that matter.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A clipboard with small labeled slips.

⸻

FG-99 — Post-Decision Action Clock (Rehearing • Mandate • Costs)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: The next 30 days decide the rest.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Table: Event • Due • Rule • Pin (rehearing/ en banc; mandate; bill of costs FRAP 39; stay window). Publish it; add to status letter.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 5-row action clock for your case.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Rehearing due 14d (FRAP 40); costs 14d (FRAP 39); stay ask 7d.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: A clock beats a paragraph.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A calendar strip with three bright due flags.

⸻

FG-100 — Institutional Memory Kit (ZIP + README + Hashes)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Package the case so others can reuse it tomorrow.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: ZIP: README (roadmap) • CHECKSUMS.txt • Pin Atlas • OA packet • orders/snippets • index; include capture dates & hashes.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build your kit list; export ZIP; add one-line repo note.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Kit.zip—StartHere.md; Atlas.pdf; OA_6pp.pdf; Orders.md; CHECKSUMS.txt (SHA-256 listed).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Memory scales impact.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A ribboned folder with a fingerprint tag.